Part One: Binary Classification

I am choosing ROC AUC as my metric because it is the best metric that gives you the overall picture, the overall evaluation of the models. If there was a specific question or specific business question we are trying to answer, I would consider looking at other metrics.

For example, if I was concerned with specifically the true postive rate I would focus more on recall or sensitivity.

QDA is not the best fit for the data because it classified everything as Sativa. SVM did not perform well as it distinguished everything as indica. LDA did well distinguishing sativa from indica.

ctnew = ct[(ct['Type']=='sativa') | (ct['Type']=='indica')]
X = ctnew.drop(['Type','Strain', 'Effects','Flavor'], axis = 1)

y = ctnew['Type']
# Confusion Matrix function

def confusion_matrix_pic(model_name,pipeline, X, y):
    '''
    Makes a confusion matrix visualization

    Parameter
    --------
    model_name : str
    fitted_model: fitted pipeline
    y : panda series of target variable
    y_pred: panda series from fitted_model.predict(X)

    Returns
    -------
    ggplot confusion matrix using plotnine

    '''
    # Fitted pipeline
    fitted_pipeline = pipeline.fit(X, y)

    # Predictions
    y_pred = fitted_pipeline.predict(X)

    # Dataframe
    kncm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    kncm_df = pd.DataFrame(kncm, index=fitted_pipeline.classes_, columns=fitted_pipeline.classes_)
    kncm_df = kncm_df.unstack().reset_index()
    kncm_df.columns = ['Predicted', 'True', 'Count']
    kncm_df

    # Plot confusion matrix using plotnine
    plot = (
    ggplot(kncm_df, aes(x='Predicted', y='True', fill='Count')) +
    geom_tile(color='white') +
    geom_text(aes(label='Count'), size=10, color='black') +
    labs(title=f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name}', x='Predicted', y='True') + # the f is for f-string to include model name
    theme_minimal()
    )
    return plot

Part Two: Natural Multiclass

My metrics were worse than in Part One becasue there is another category which is difficult to distinguish. The most categoires that were most likely to get mixed up were hybrid with any other type. Hybrid is a mix of both types which doesnât always provide clear classification compared to distinguishing between sativa and indica.

This is One v. Rest. So appropriate metrics to use in this multiclass setting is accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 Score.

Accuracy is the only metric that is truly a multiclass metric.

I did not consider micro/macro/weighted average because there is no specific interest in a singular category at this time.

ct2 = ct.drop(['Strain','Effects','Flavor'], axis = 1)

# Decision Tree plot

dtfitted = dtpipeline.fit(X1,y1)

# use this to get column names to use in feature names argument
feature_names = X1.columns.tolist()

# Export the decision tree to a DOT file
dot_data = export_graphviz(dtfitted.named_steps['dt'],
                           feature_names = feature_names,
                           class_names = dtfitted.named_steps['dt'].classes_.astype(str),
                           filled = True,
                           rounded = True,
                           special_characters = True,
                           out_file = None)

# Render the decision tree

graph = graphviz.Source(dot_data, format = 'png')
display(Image(graph.render(format='png', cleanup = True)))

Interpretation: One way to read this is that if someone is feeling sleepy, citrusy, and uplifted or not uplifted, it is indica. Starting at the top of the tree, if someone feels more sleepy look at the false side. If someone feels less sleepy, look at the true side. As we can see, the tree classified many indicas and hybrids and only classified sativa once.
